2. Original DraculaForge palettes — Apache 2.0 (Julien Bombled)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Fourteen palettes engineered with honest HSL targets (computed from declared
parameters, not reverse-engineered from hand-picked hexes) :

  * All 10 Dark variants share an identical 7-accent band at HSL
    L 0.68 / S 0.65, with hues fixed at Cyan 186°, Green 135°, Orange 27°,
    Pink 333°, Purple 282°, Red 0°, Yellow 60°. Only the Background hue
    rotates between variants — the 7 accent hex values are byte-identical
    across the 10 Darks.

  * The 2 Light variants share an accent band at L 0.32 / S 0.78. Darker
    and more saturated than the Dark band so accents remain legible on the
    high-luminance L 0.95 backgrounds (clears WCAG AA on every accent).

  * The 2 Alt variants reuse the Dark band but break exactly one accent
    for their signature. The break holds same L 0.68 as the base band but
    elevates S to 0.82 — equal luminance keeps the signature visually paired
    with the rest of the band, chroma alone sets it apart. This is a design
    choice over the visually noisier L-bump approach.

  Dark family (Background hue / character)
  - Striga          H  12°   Romanian night-witch, warm umber
  - Cinder           H  50°   mourning hearth, warm amber
  - Bracken             H 110°   graveyard yew, bottle-green
  - Tarn            H 160°   highland tarn, petrol-teal
  - Mortis          H 200°   slate-cyan morgue
  - Slate           H 220°   cold monastery stone, slate-blue
  - Voivode         H 250°   Wallachian throne, deep indigo
  - Carmilla        H 285°   velvet violet, Styrian countess (Le Fanu 1872)
  - Whitby          H 315°   North Sea slate-mauve, where Dracula came ashore
  - Vesper          H 340°   evening prayer in a ruined chapel

  Light family
  - Parchment       H  40°   warm vellum cream, scholarly hush
  - Folio          H 220°   cool ivory, stained-glass morning

  Alt family
  - Wormwood        Green broken to viridian (H 158°) — Green Fairy / absinthe
  - Sconce          Orange broken to amber (H 38°)   — Victorian sconce

All names are drawn from public domain sources : folklore (Striga, Bracken, Tarn,
Mortis), architecture (Sconce, Folio, Parchment), atmosphere (Cinder, Vesper,
Slate), historical figures (Voivode = Romanian "warlord", Vlad III's title),
literature (Carmilla 1872, Whitby = Stoker 1897 setting), and herbal/biblical
references (Wormwood = Revelation 8:11 + Lewis's Screwtape Letters).

The "Dracula" name and Dracula PRO product are trademarks of Zeno Rocha. No
commercial Dracula PRO scheme name (Pro, Alucard, Blade, Buffy, Lincoln,
Morbius, Van Helsing) appears in this set.

================================================================================
Cross-review history
================================================================================

The v3 palette set is the result of a independent audit performed on
2026-05-18 :

  - an independent reviewer     — see NOTICE
  - an independent reviewer          — see NOTICE
  - an independent reviewer         — see NOTICE
  - Synthesis           — see NOTICE

Major changes vs v2 :
  - Honest HSL claims (v2 claimed L 0.74 / S 0.66 ; actual was L 0.68 / S 0.65)
  - Light accent band darkened to clear WCAG AA on bright surfaces
  - Comment colors lifted ~6 L points to clear AA on Bg AND CurrentLine
  - 4 Dark variants retired (Belfry, Sepulcher, Stygian, Nosferatu) to
    eliminate Background hue clumps
  - 3 Dark variants added (Cinder, Bracken, Tarn) to fill the 30°-180° wheel gap
  - 4 renames : Drakula→Voivode (intra-set collision), Mireille→Mortis
    (tonal mismatch), Lucent→Folio (Lucent Technologies brand collision),
    Gaslight→Sconce (gaslighting connotation)
  - Drakula→Voivode Bg darkened from L 0.24 to L 0.14 (fixes accent AA failures)

================================================================================
Architectural inspiration
================================================================================

The theming engine architecture (IThemeService + ThemeRevision pattern,
ResourceDictionary swap, design tokens, semantic brush layering) is inspired
by the internal theming of Heimdall.Next (https://github.com/jbombled/Heimdall.Next),
authored by the same person. No source code from Heimdall.Next is copied
into this repository ; only the pattern is reused.
